{"id":"ebbetts-pass","generatedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z","designation":"National Scenic Byway","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"Ebbetts Pass","revisionId":1362432758,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ebbetts_Pass"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ebbetts_Pass","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"Ebbetts Pass\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ebbetts_Pass","revisionId":1362432758,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"}],"endpoints":null,"itinerary":[{"place":"Ebbetts Pass (start)","mileFromStart":0,"kind":"terminus","lat":38.26077,"lng":-120.33872,"seq":1,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"The drive begins here","toNextMi":2.1},{"place":"Scenic overlook","mileFromStart":2.1,"kind":"overlook","lat":38.27264,"lng":-120.29952,"seq":2,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":15.2},{"place":"Liberty Vista Point","mileFromStart":17.3,"kind":"overlook","lat":38.40932,"lng":-120.13695,"seq":3,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":3.2},{"place":"Hell's Kitchen Vista Point","mileFromStart":20.5,"kind":"overlook","lat":38.42279,"lng":-120.08374,"seq":4,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":13.8},{"place":"Pacific Grade Summit","mileFromStart":34.3,"kind":"crossing","lat":38.51658,"lng":-119.90935,"seq":5,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":7.8},{"place":"Ebbetts Pass","mileFromStart":42.1,"kind":"crossing","lat":38.54431,"lng":-119.81191,"seq":6,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":15.6},{"place":"Ebbetts Pass (end)","mileFromStart":57.7,"kind":"terminus","lat":38.68442,"lng":-119.75321,"seq":7,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"The drive ends here"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["Native Americans were undoubtedly the first humans to traverse the Sierra Nevada Mountains, but it is unknown if they regularly used Ebbetts Pass since any trail they would have used is no longer traceable. It is traditionally held to be the pass used by Jedediah Smith in late spring of 1827 when leaving California at the end of his first exploratory journey, the first crossing ever of the Sierra Nevada by a non-native, but snow would have obscured any trail so he was blazing his own path. It may also have been used by the Bartleson–Bidwell Party on their emigration to California.","John Ebbetts, a fur trader turned guide for California Gold Rush \"Forty-niners\" claimed to have led a string of pack mules easterly over the Sierras in the vicinity of Ebbetts Pass in April 1851. He believed the pass he had used would be suitable for the transcontinental railroad, as he noted little snow at the time. He later surveyed near the pass for a possible railroad route, but found it unsuitable. He intended to return to the pass itself to survey it for a road but was killed in the explosion of the steamboat Secretary on San Pablo Bay in 1854 before he could do so. While the pass was referred to by his name earlier, it was not until 1893, when the U.S. Geological Survey surveyed the Markleeville quadrangle, that the pass was officially named after him.","The route was used only occasionally until silver was discovered east of the Sierra, and merchants in Murphys had a road constructed to Markleeville to more easily transport supplies over the pass to the miners. This became a toll road in 1862. From Markleeville, travel further eastward was taken along established routes.","It was not until the early 1950s that the road over Monitor Pass to U.S. Route 395 was completed, connecting the eastern terminus of State Route 4 to U.S. Route 395 via State Route 89 near the community of Topaz."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"\"Ebbetts Pass\". Geographic Names Information System. United States Geological Survey, United States Department of the Interior. Retrieved 2012-06-23.","url":"https://edits.nationalmap.gov/apps/gaz-domestic/public/search/names/259784"},{"n":2,"text":"\"T 194\". NGS Data Sheet. National Geodetic Survey, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, United States Department of Commerce. Retrieved 2012-06-23.","url":"https://www.ngs.noaa.gov/cgi-bin/ds_mark.prl?PidBox=JR0564"},{"n":3,"text":"\"Ebbetts Pass Route\". Office of Historic Preservation, California State Parks. Retrieved 2012-03-30.","url":"https://ohp.parks.ca.gov/ListedResources/Detail/318"},{"n":4,"text":"Marvin, Judith. \"Ebbetts Pass History\". CalaverasHistory.org. Retrieved 2019-06-15.","url":"http://www.calaverashistory.org/overview/ebbetts-pass-history"},{"n":5,"text":"\"History\". Ebbetts Pass National Scenic Byway. Retrieved 2019-06-15.","url":"https://scenic4.org/history/"},{"n":6,"text":"Gudde, Erwin Gustav (2004). California Place Names: The Origin and Etymology of Current Geographical Names. University of California Press. ISBN 0-520-24217-3.","url":"https://books.google.com/books?id=Kqwt5RlMVBoC&q=john+ebbetts&pg=PA118"},{"n":7,"text":"\"State Route 89\". California Highways. Retrieved 2007-11-04.","url":"http://www.cahighways.org/089-096.html#089"},{"n":8,"text":"\"Ebbetts Pass Scenic Byway\".","url":"http://www.scenic4.org"}],"routeLine":[[38.26077,-120.33872],[38.26144,-120.33785],[38.26193,-120.33729],[38.26245,-120.33682],[38.26331,-120.33618],[38.26398,-120.3356],[38.26446,-120.33487],[38.265,-120.3337],[38.26539,-120.33299],[38.26588,-120.33242],[38.26645,-120.33201],[38.26705,-120.33175],[38.267